revision.text:
[[File:Quema de libros.jpg|thumb|200px|Chilean soldiers burn books considered politically subversive in 1973, under [[Augusto Pinochet]]'s dictatorship.]] '''Book censorship''' is when some authority, government or otherwise, takes measures to prevent access to a book or to part of its contents. It can be enacted at the national or subnational level, and can carry legal penalties. Books may also be [[Challenge (literature)|challenged]] at a local community level, although successful bans do not extend outside that area. Similarly, religions may issue lists of banned books—a historical example being the [[Roman Catholic Church]]'s ''[[Index Librorum Prohibitorum]]''—which do not always carry legal force.
==Background== "Almost every country places some restrictions on what may be published, although the emphasis and the degree of control differ from country to country and at different periods."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/censorship-of-books/1|title=CENSORSHIP OF BOOKS|work=teara.govt.nz}}</ref> There are a variety of reasons for which books may be banned. Materials are often suppressed due to the perceived notion of obscenity. This obscenity can apply to materials that are about sexuality, race, drugs, or social standing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/bbooks/about|title=About Banned & Challenged Books|work=ala.org}}</ref> The censorship of literature on the charge of obscenity appears to have begun in the early 19th century.<ref name="universityofsouthflorida">{{cite web|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=rfh&AN=ATLA0000696290&site=eds-live|title=USF NetID Single-SignOn - University of South Florida|author=University of South Florida|work=usf.edu}}</ref> The rise of the middle class, who had evangelical backgrounds, brought about this concern with obscenity.<ref name="universityofsouthflorida"/>
Governments have also sought to ban certain books which they perceive to contain material that could threaten, embarrass, or criticize them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/banned-books.html|title=Banned Books Online|work=upenn.edu}}</ref>
Other leaders outside the government have banned books, including religious authorities.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | title = Index Librorum Prohibitorum | encyclopedia = Encyclopædia Britannica Online}}</ref> Church leaders who prohibit members of their faith from reading the banned books may want to shelter them from perceived obscene, immoral, or profane ideas or situations or from ideas that may challenge the teaching of that religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=54091811&site=eds-live|title=USF NetID Single-SignOn - University of South Florida|author=University of South Florida|work=usf.edu}}</ref>
But even religious materials have been subject to censorship. For example, various [[religious text|scriptures]] have been banned (and sometimes burned at several points in history). The [[Bible]], and other religious scriptures have all been subjected to censorship and have been banned by various governments. Similarly, books based on the scriptures have also been banned, such as [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s ''[[The Kingdom of God Is Within You]]'', which was banned in the [[Russian Empire]] for being [[anti-establishment]].<ref>http://sitemaker.umich.edu/globalnonviolence/files/tolstoy.pdf</ref>
Banning of a book often has the effect of making people [[Streisand effect|seek the book]].<ref name="npr.org">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/09/20/224427254/could-banning-books-actually-encourage-more-readers|title=Could Banning Books Actually Encourage More Readers?|date=20 September 2013|work=NPR.org}}</ref> The action of banning the book creates an interest in the book which has the opposite effect of making the work more popular.<ref name="npr.org"/>
==Book burning== [[Book burning]] is the practice of destroying, often ceremonially, books or other written material. It is usually carried out in public, and is generally motivated by moral, religious, or political objections to the material, with a desire to censor it.
