A '''cement bond log''' documents the evaluation of the integrity of [[cement]] work performed on an [[oil well]].<ref name="OilfieldGlossary1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/Display.cfm?Term=cement%20bond%20log|title=cement bond log|accessdate=2008-12-18|publisher=Schlumberger Limited|work=Oilfield Glossary}}</ref> In the process of drilling and completing a well, cement is injected through the [[wellbore]] and rises up the [[Annulus (well)|annulus]] between the steel [[Casing (borehole)|casing]] and the [[Geological formation|formation]].<ref name="OilfieldGlossary2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/Display.cfm?Term=casing|title=casing|accessdate=2008-12-18|publisher=Schlumberger Limited|work=Oilfield Glossary}}</ref>

A sonic tool is typically run on [[wireline (cabling)|wireline]] by a service company that detects the bond of the cement to the casing and formation via a principle based on [[resonance]]. Casing that is not bound has a higher resonant vibration than that which is bound, causing the imparted energy from the sonic signal to be transferred to the formation.{{Fact|date=December 2008}} In this sense, the [[amplitude]] of the [[waveform]] received is the basic measurement that is evaluated.

The data is collected by the tool and recorded on a log which is used by the oil producing company as an indicator of [[zonal isolation]] in the well. There are production reasons and legal reasons (governed by a petroleum regulatory body in each individual state) that dictate the well must have specific areas of isolation.{{Fact|date=December 2008}}

