'''Methyl green-pyronin (MGP)''' is a classical [[Histology#Staining|histological staining]] technique using two [[base (chemistry)|basic]] (cationic) dyes for the demonstration and differentiation of [[DNA]] and [[RNA]]. [[Methyl green]] is specific for [[phosphate]] [[radical (chemistry)|radicals]] in the [[Nucleic acid double helix|DNA double helix]] staining it green-blue. [[Pyronin]] does not possess this affinity and binds to the remaining negatively charged RNA staining it red. The method is useful in identifying the distribution of [[Nissl substance]] in [[neuron]]al cell bodies.<ref>Suvarna, S.K., Layton, C. and Bancroft, J.D. 2013, ''Bancroft's Theory and Practice of Histological Techniques'', 7th edn, Churchill Livingstone Elsevier</ref>

