'''Resistance paper''',<ref name="Kraus">"The outline (or boundaries)of the trough are drawn on the resistance paper with silver (conducting) paint. ... Another field-mapping arrangement using resistance paper is shown ...a pantograph for transferring equipotential points from the resistance paper to ...resistance-paper analog." {{cite book| last=Kraus|first= John D. | year= 1984|title=Electromagnetics |edition=3rd |publisher=McGraw-Hill |isbn=0-07-035423-5 | p=295–297}}</ref><ref name="Marshall">"...commonly used laboratory setups are the uniform resistance paper, such as Teledeltos paper, ..." {{cite book| last=Marshall|first= Stanley V.|last2=Skitek|first2=Gabriel G. | year= 1987|title=Electromagnetic Concepts & Applications |edition=2nd |publisher=Prentice-Hall |isbn=0-13-249004-8 | p=201}}</ref> also known as '''conductive paper''' and by the trade name '''[[Teledeltos]] paper''' is paper impregnated or coated with a conductive substance such that the paper exhibits a uniform and known [[surface resistivity]].  Resistance paper and [[conductive ink]] were commonly used as an analog two-dimensional<ref name="Ramo">"Resistance paper is very simple to use for two-dimensional problems..." {{cite book|last= Ramo|first= Simon |last2= Whinnery|first2= John R. |last3= van Duzer|first3= Theodore|year= 1965 |title= Fields and Waves in Communication Electronics |publisher= John Wiley | p=168–170}}</ref> [[electromagnetic field solver]].  [[Teledeltos]] paper is a particular type of resistance paper.

