{{Infobox book | name = Why Does E=mc²? | image = Why Does Emc².jpg | caption = Paperback edition | author = [[Brian Cox (physicist)|Brian Cox]], [[Jeff Forshaw]] | language = English | genre = Non-fiction | subject = Physics, [[theory of relativity]] | country = United States | publisher = [[Da Capo Press]] | pub_date = July 14, 2009 | media_type = Print ([[hardcover]]) | pages = 264 pp. | isbn = 978-0306818769 | preceded_by = | followed_by = [[Wonders of the Solar System (book)|Wonders of the Solar System]] }}
'''''Why Does E=mc²? (And Why Should We Care?)''''' is a 2009 book by the [[Theoretical physics|theoretical physicists]] [[Brian Cox (physicist)|Brian Cox]] and [[Jeff Forshaw]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Why Does E=mc²? (And Why Should We Care?) by Brian Cox, Jeffrey R. Forshaw|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5958783-why-does-e-mc|website=[[Goodreads]]|publisher=goodreads.com|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> This was the first full-scale book from Professors Cox and Forshaw.
==Overview== The book aims to provide an explanation of the [[theory of relativity]] that is accessible to a general reader. The authors also explain what [[Albert Einstein|Einstein’s]] most famous equation, [[Mass–energy equivalence|E=mc²]] stands for.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Why Does E=mc²? by Brian Cox and Jeff Forshaw – review|url = https://www.theguardian.com/science/2010/oct/18/einstein-relativity-science-book-review|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-11-21|first = Alok|last = Jha}}</ref>
